<subSubSection id="A6D16572E80BFF84FF4DE0A5FB0AF956" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" type="description">
<paragraph id="EE7436F9E80BFF84FF4DE0A5FB0AF956" blockId="15.[151,1436,1519,1690]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
This monotypic genus is known from only four specimens of a unique species, 
<taxonomicName id="29CB4D7AE80BFF84FB98E0A5FF42F9E1" authority="(Bruner, 1900)" baseAuthorityName="Bruner" baseAuthorityYear="1900" class="Insecta" family="Tetrigidae" genus="Lophoscirtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis id="DCBFEAEBE80BFF84FB98E0A5FAAEF9C5" box="[1090,1333,1519,1545]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Lophoscirtus gracilis</emphasis>
(Bruner, 1900)
</taxonomicName>
found in 
<collectingCountry id="96DC7669E80BFF84FE9FE359FE2FF9E1" box="[325,436,1555,1581]" name="Argentina" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="2C0FF81BE80BFF84FE1EE359FDA7F9E2" box="[452,572,1555,1582]" country="Argentina" name="Corrientes" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Corrientes</collectingRegion>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="96DC7669E80BFF84FDA1E35EFD46F9E2" box="[635,733,1556,1582]" name="Uruguay" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="2C0FF81BE80BFF84FD36E359FCECF9E2" box="[748,887,1555,1582]" country="Uruguay" name="Montevideo" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Montevideo</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation id="76F02A7CE80BFF84FC55E359FC7FF9E1" box="[911,996,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1959,1983]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,990,1935]" captionTargetId="figure-39@45.[151,1436,990,1936]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 37. Map of approximated occurrence of the genera Puiggaria Bolívar, 1887; Halmatettix Hancock, 1909; Lophoscirtus Bruner, 1910 and Paurotarsus Hancock, 1900." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4614468" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4614468/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
). This species is characterized by body elongated, slightly flattened; antennae with 17 segments; middle femur with a tiny, internal, dorso-apical spine and, the most important morphological aspect in the head, that does not permit it to be confused with any known batrachideine: frontal costa (lateral view) protrusive, almost horn-like (
<bibRefCitation id="8A5A4B08E80BFF84FC6EE335FBA6F956" author="Grant Jr., H. J." box="[948,1085,1663,1690]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" pagination="67 - 108" refId="ref22611" refString="Grant Jr., H. J. (1956) The taxonomy of Batrachidea, Puiggaria, Lophoscirtus, Eutettigidea and Rehnidium n. gen. (Orthotpera: Acridoidea, Tetrigidae). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 82, 67 - 108." type="journal article" year="1956">Grant, 1956</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="8A5A4B08E80BFF84FB92E335FB1FF956" author="Grant, H. J." box="[1096,1156,1663,1690]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refId="ref22659" refString="Grant, H. J. (1962) A revision of the subfamily Batrachideinae (Orthoptera; Tetrigidae). PhD Thesis, University of Colorado Library, University of Colorado, Colorado, 208 pp." type="book" year="1962">1962</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
